      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#191817;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        How Brisbane sellers should communicate with their agent during the campaign
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(25,24,23,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        The relationship between seller and agent is one of the most under-prepared parts of a property sale. Here is the cadence, the questions, and the channels that keep a Brisbane campaign on track.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The standard advice on choosing a real estate agent ends at the moment the Form 6 is signed. What happens next is almost never discussed and almost always determines how the campaign feels: the daily texts, the post-open-home phone calls, the Wednesday-night debrief, the awkward conversation about reducing the price, the question of whether to accept the early offer. The communication during the campaign is where the relationship is actually tested.</p>

      <p>Most Brisbane sellers go into their first campaign without a clear sense of how often they should be talking to their agent, what questions are useful, what channels work best, and what a healthy back-and-forth looks like. The result is one of two failure modes. Some sellers under-communicate, hear from the agent only at the weekly debrief, miss critical signals, and feel out of control. Others over-communicate, message the agent every time an inspector raises an eyebrow, exhaust both sides, and turn every passing comment into a crisis. The right pattern is in between, and it can be set up deliberately in the first conversation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Set the communication cadence in week one</h2>

      <p>Before the campaign launches, agree the cadence in plain terms. The conversation should cover three things: how often you will speak each week, which day the formal debrief happens, and which channels are used for what. A typical Brisbane campaign benefits from a fixed weekly call (usually Monday or Tuesday after the weekend open home), text-message updates after each midweek inspection, and a phone call for anything that needs a decision.</p>

      <p>Sellers who set the cadence up front avoid two predictable problems. The first is the agent who goes quiet between open homes because nothing has happened and they have no news to deliver. Silence is not absence of news; it is news, and it deserves a brief update. The second is the agent who calls at random moments throughout the week with fragments of information that are not yet useful. A predictable cadence forces both sides to gather their thinking before talking.</p>

      <p>Be explicit about the times that do not work for you. If you take calls at lunch but not during the school run, say so. If you cannot focus on a debrief on Sunday evening because you are still processing the open home, schedule it for Monday morning. The agent will adapt, and you will start the campaign with a clear protocol rather than negotiating it under pressure later.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the weekly debrief should cover</h2>

      <p>The weekly debrief is the single most important communication of the campaign. It is the moment where the raw inputs (inspector counts, buyer comments, online listing analytics, competing properties) are converted into a decision about the next seven days. A debrief that drifts into general chat without producing a clear plan is a debrief that has failed.</p>

      <p>A useful debrief covers four blocks. First, the inspector volume and quality: how many people came through, how many were serious, who is returning for a second look. Second, the feedback grouped by category: price, presentation, layout, location, marketing, with the agent flagging which comments came from serious buyers versus passing inspectors. Third, the comparable activity: what listed nearby this week, what sold, what reduced its price, and how those moves affect your positioning. Fourth, the plan for the coming week: target inspector numbers, any specific buyers expected to return, any campaign adjustments under consideration.</p>

      <p>Ask for a written summary after the debrief. A two-paragraph email captures the agreed actions, gives you something to refer back to, and prevents the slow drift that happens when each week's conversation is held only verbally. Good agents are happy to provide this. Agents who resist a written summary are usually the ones who later argue that "we agreed something different last week."</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The questions worth asking</h2>

      <p>The most useful questions during a campaign are specific, comparative, and behavioural. How many serious buyers do we have in the pipeline? Which buyers have returned for a second inspection? Who has taken the contract to their solicitor? Which inspectors are still considering, and which have moved on to a different property? What did you learn this week that you did not know last week?</p>

      <p>Compare those with the less useful questions sellers tend to default to. "Is the open home going well?" produces a reassuring answer that contains no information. "What did people say?" produces an unfiltered list of comments that you cannot rank. "Are we going to get our price?" puts the agent in a position to either over-promise or generate anxiety, neither of which helps.</p>

      <p>Behavioural questions are the highest-value of all. The number of buyers who have ordered a building and pest report is a better read on serious interest than the number of inspectors. The number of buyers whose solicitor has phoned the listing office tells you more than the number of cards left at the open home. Train yourself to ask about actions, not opinions, and the campaign signal becomes much clearer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Channels: when to call, text, or email</h2>

      <p>Different channels suit different content, and matching them well reduces friction on both sides. Text messages are best for short updates that do not require a response: the inspector count after a midweek inspection, the confirmation that photography is rebooked, the heads-up that an offer is coming through later today. Phone calls are best for anything that involves a decision: a price reduction, an offer to consider, a contract change request, a campaign reset. Email is best for anything that needs a written record: the weekly summary, the contract draft, the marketing brief, the agreed actions for the next week.</p>

      <p>Agents who default to phone calls for everything tend to deliver more emotion than information; the back-and-forth of a call makes it harder to think clearly about a complex offer or a campaign reset. Agents who default to email tend to lose the nuance of a serious conversation; written words on price can come across more abruptly than the same words spoken. The right mix uses each channel for what it is good at, and a Brisbane vendor can ask their agent to follow this pattern from day one.</p>

      <p>Voice notes are an underused middle ground. A two-minute voice message from an agent after a buyer phone call, summarising what was said and the next step, gives more context than a text and more flexibility than a scheduled call. If the agent's office uses voice notes, lean into them for the in-between updates that do not warrant a full call but need more than a single sentence.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Reading between the lines of an agent's report</h2>

      <p>Experienced agents communicate in a calibrated register. The language is professional, the framing is constructive, and the bad news is wrapped in context. That register is generally a feature, not a bug, but it does mean sellers need to know how to read the signals that are being softened.</p>

      <p>"The market is taking its time to absorb this campaign" usually means inspector numbers are below where the agent expected. "We are still gathering serious feedback" usually means no serious feedback has yet emerged. "The price expectation may need to be reviewed" almost always means it needs to be reduced. None of these phrases is dishonest, but each of them is gentler than the underlying data. If a phrase feels softened, ask the explicit question: "Is inspector volume below where you expected at this point?" The honest answer is usually yes, and surfacing it earlier means you can act on it earlier.</p>

      <p>Equally, learn the language of genuine progress. "Two buyers are coming back for a second inspection," "their solicitor called this morning," "we have a written offer coming through this afternoon": these are unambiguous signals. The campaign is moving when the agent's language describes actions rather than impressions.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When the agent has bad news</h2>

      <p>Bad news in a campaign is rarely a single event. Far more often it is a slow accumulation: inspector numbers below target for two weeks, no second inspections, a competing property listing fifty thousand dollars below where yours sits. The agent's job is to surface this honestly and early, and your job is to make that honesty easy to deliver.</p>

      <p>Sellers who react sharply to bad news encourage their agent to soften the next round. The agent learns to delay the difficult conversation, present the numbers in their best light, and avoid being the messenger. By the time the situation is undeniable, weeks have passed and the options have narrowed. A seller who takes bad news calmly, asks specific follow-up questions, and works the problem with the agent gets the next round delivered earlier and more directly.</p>

      <p>The practical move is to acknowledge bad news first and ask questions second. "Thank you for telling me that directly. What do we know about why? What are our options from here?" creates the conversation you need. "Why is this happening?" delivered in a sharp tone shuts it down. The agent is your most informed ally during the campaign, and the way you respond to difficult news determines how informed you stay.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Disagreements: how to push back constructively</h2>

      <p>You will not agree with every recommendation the agent makes. The price reduction they propose may feel premature. The auction strategy they want to use may not match your preference. The buyer they are advocating for may not feel like the right fit. Disagreement is part of a healthy campaign, and the way you handle it determines whether the agent's expertise stays available to you.</p>

      <p>Push back by asking for the reasoning, not by overriding the recommendation. "Help me understand why you think a fifty-thousand-dollar reduction now is better than waiting two more weeks at this price." That question makes the agent show their working. Sometimes the working is solid and you change your view. Sometimes the working is thin and the agent will retreat to a different recommendation. Either way, you have moved the conversation from a clash of preferences to a comparison of evidence.</p>

      <p>If you decide to override the recommendation, document the decision and the agent's view. "I have decided to hold at the current price for two more weeks despite your recommendation to reduce; we will review at the next debrief." That single sentence in an email protects the relationship by making clear that the agent's advice was given, considered, and respectfully not taken on this occasion. It also gives you a clear reference point in two weeks when you review whether the call was right.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The "no offers" conversation</h2>

      <p>Few campaign moments are harder than the conversation after three or four weeks without a serious offer. The agent is delivering news you did not want to hear. You are facing decisions about price, marketing refresh, and method of sale that all have cost and discomfort attached. This is the conversation where the communication patterns you set in week one pay off the most.</p>

      <p>Ask the agent to come to that meeting with three options, not one. Option one might be a meaningful price reduction with a refreshed photography set. Option two might be a method change, for example from private treaty to an expressions-of-interest campaign with a defined closing date. Option three might be a tactical pause: take the listing off the market for a fortnight, address a specific weakness (styling, photography, headline copy), then relaunch. A good agent will have a view on which of the three has the best chance, but presenting all three forces the trade-offs to be visible.</p>

      <p>Take twenty-four hours after that meeting before deciding. Decisions made under the emotional weight of a slow campaign are often the wrong ones. A night to compare the options, look at the underlying data, and check the recommendation against what you have heard from buyers usually produces a better call than a same-day commitment.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What NOT to do</h2>

      <p>Do not message the agent multiple times a day. Every inspector comment, every online view spike, every neighbour's casual remark does not warrant a message. High-volume contact erodes the agent's ability to think clearly about your campaign and signals that you are anxious, which is information the agent has to manage on top of running the sale. Save the high-frequency contact for the moments when something genuinely material has happened.</p>

      <p>Do not bypass the agent to talk to buyers directly. Some Brisbane sellers, especially those who have met inspectors at open homes, are tempted to follow up themselves with a buyer who showed interest. This is almost always counterproductive. It complicates the negotiation, it can breach the agent's authority, and it gives the buyer a second voice with different framing. The agent represents you for a reason; let them.</p>

      <p>Do not surprise the agent with major decisions. If you are considering taking the property off the market, switching from auction to private treaty, or refusing an offer the agent considers strong, walk the agent through your reasoning first. They may agree, they may push back with information you did not have, and either way the decision is better for the conversation. Agents who hear about a major seller decision after the fact lose confidence that the relationship is collaborative.</p>

      <p>Do not let small frustrations accumulate without raising them. If the agent's reports are too vague, if the open-home photography looks dated, if the weekly debrief keeps getting rescheduled, say so at the next meeting. Small frustrations raised early are easy to resolve. The same frustrations carried in silence for four weeks turn into resentment, and resentment makes every later decision harder.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The closing weeks</h2>

      <p>Communication in the closing weeks of a campaign shifts character. If offers are coming through, the focus moves to negotiation tactics, contract terms, and the order in which buyers should be played against each other. If no offers have arrived, the focus moves to the harder conversations about reset, method change, or extension. Either way, the cadence intensifies, the calls get more frequent, and the email trail gets denser.</p>

      <p>Keep the weekly debrief in place even when daily contact has ramped up. The debrief is where the week is summarised and the next phase is decided; the daily contact is where the tactical moves happen. Losing the weekly summary in the noise of the daily contact is a common mistake. The summary keeps the campaign coherent and prevents the closing weeks from feeling like a stream of disconnected decisions.</p>

      <p>If the campaign closes with a successful sale, the communication continues through the contract conditions period and settlement. If the campaign closes without a sale and you are considering relisting, the post-campaign debrief is one of the most useful conversations of the whole process. The agent has seen the buyer pool, the competing stock, the marketing response, and the feedback patterns. The frankness of that debrief usually shapes the next campaign more than any other input.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>

      <p>Communication during a Brisbane campaign is a discipline, not a personality trait. Set the cadence in week one. Hold a structured weekly debrief that ends in a written summary. Ask about behaviour rather than opinion. Match the channel to the content. Treat bad news calmly so you keep getting it early. Push back by asking for reasoning. Document overrides. Keep the contact predictable rather than reactive.</p>

      <p>The agent's expertise is a resource that becomes more useful the more deliberately you draw on it. Sellers who set up clear communication patterns from day one end up with a calmer campaign, better decisions at the pressure points, and a clearer read on what their property is actually worth in the current market.</p>

